Sentence: She got fired last Friday.
She : pronoun, third person singular, feminine, subject of the verb "got"
got : auxiliary verb "get", past tense, forms a dynamic passive indicating an event or change of state rather than a static condition
fired : past participle of the verb "fire", functions as the main predicate in the passive construction, implies an action happened to the subject
last : adjective, modifies "Friday", indicates time
Friday : proper noun, day of the week, adverbial of time

Sentence: He got promoted to manager yesterday.
He : pronoun, third person singular, masculine, subject of the verb "got"
got : auxiliary verb "get", past tense, suggests a personal achievement or specific event unlike the neutral "was"
promoted : past participle of the verb "promote", describes the action received by the subject
to : preposition, introduces the new role
manager : noun, common, object of the preposition "to"
yesterday : adverb, indicates time

Sentence: The dog got hurt in the park.
The : definite article, specifies the noun "dog"
dog : noun, common, singular, subject of the verb "got"
got : auxiliary verb "get", past tense, emphasizes the occurrence of an unfortunate event or accident
hurt : past participle of the verb "hurt", describes the physical state resulting from the event
in : preposition, indicates location
the : definite article, specifies the noun "park"
park : noun, common, singular, object of the preposition "in"

Sentence: They got invited to the wedding.
They : pronoun, third person plural, subject of the verb "got"
got : auxiliary verb "get", past tense, implies receiving an invitation as a specific occurrence rather than a general state
invited : past participle of the verb "invite", functions as the passive verb
to : preposition, indicates direction or destination
the : definite article, specifies the noun "wedding"
wedding : noun, common, singular, object of the preposition "to"

Sentence: My car got stolen overnight.
My : possessive adjective, modifies "car"
car : noun, common, singular, subject of the verb "got"
got : auxiliary verb "get", past tense, highlights the suddenness or negative nature of the event compared to "was"
stolen : past participle of the verb "steal", indicates the action performed on the subject
overnight : adverb, indicates the time duration when the event occurred

